description.value: Limestone pilaster from Horemheb's first tomb: showing the generalissimo with his hands raised in prayer. The prayer of this figure, which faced east, is offered to the traditional sun god, Ra, in his rising; while that on the opposite side, above his figure facing west, is to Osiris, Foremost god of the West . Horemheb wears an extremely elaborate court costume, typical of the late Eighteenth Dynasty: a long, elaborate crimped and curled double wig, to which the uraeus was added, and several layers of clothing - all of it, apparently, in diaphanous pleated linen. Over a shirt with wide, floppy sleeves there seem to be at least two kilts, from one of which hangs a long pointed front panel indicating Horemheb's military status. Fastened to a shoulder strap and hanging down his back is a fan made from a single ostrich plume, insignia of Horemheb's exalted role as "Fan Bearer on the Right of the King" - that is, one who had access to the king's person. Horemheb's sandaled feet are rendered identically. His face is sweet-looking with his large, heavy-lidded eye, his rather plump, bottom-heavy figure, and his spindly limbs. Faint traces red and blue paint are still visible. The pilaster has been reassembled from the four pieces into which it was broken.

description.value: A flask with a flattened circular body decorated in relief: on each side is a narrow notched border. At the centre is a target covering the crossover point of 'straps' extending to the border. The 'straps' have ring-and-dot patterns divided by short double transverse lines. Below the mouth of the vessel is a pendent triangular 'necklace', with an ivy-leaf pendant, enclosing a simple palmette. The mouth is lost, together with most of both handles: they appear to have had grooved edges, and the lower springs are notched. Two non-functional bolster feet are placed at the bottom. On one side, adjacent to the 'necklace', are two letters of badly formed demotic, incised before firing. Two-piece mould. Micaceous dark-grey Nile silt, covered with a black slip (Memphis Black Ware).

description.value: Brown pottery pilgrim-flask with circular body, the neck is damaged and one handle is missing, the exterior is covered with a grey-coloured slip. On each side, within a plain border, Saint Menas stands to front, flanked by camels, his arms outstretched in blessing. Above his arms on side (a) are crosses; on side (b) are groups of chevrons. He has curly hair, and wears a short tunic: his cloak is only visible in its drapery across the shoulders. The saint and the camels are so close, one to another, on both sides, that a single archetype must have produced their moulds, but the differing devices above the arms point to alternative manipulation of the moulds.

description.value: A souvenir flask. On side (a), within a double border of studs, Saint Menas stands to front, his arms outstretched in blessing. Above each arm is a quincunx of raised points, forming a cross. He wears a short tunic and a long cloak, and is flanked by camels; between each camel and the fall of the cloak is a vertical line of raised points. On side (b), within a border of studs and a narrow wreath, Saint Menas is shown as before, except that the vertical lines of raised points are absent. Despite the latter variation, and the major difference of the borders, the figure of the saint, of the camels, and the appearance of the crosses are so close one to another that there must be some connection between them in the archetype/mould aspect of their production. The mouth is damaged. Buff clay, with white inclusions and a little mica.

description.value: Calcite base of pillar or libation-tank: this rectangular block on a plinth has been hollowed out in the centre to a depth of 10.5 cm. The Horus name, prenomen and nomen of Ramses II are twice incised along the sides of the piece together with epithets naming Atum and possibly Horus. This block may originally have been the base of a statue or a libation trough. This piece is cracked and broken in several places with severe loss to one side and damage to two corners. It has been restored in modern times. There are no traces of colour.
